section.t:
Stringprep defines a framework within which protocols define their
      Stringprep profiles.  Known IETF specifications using Stringprep are
      listed below:
      
        The Nameprep profile  for use in
        Internationalized Domain Names (IDNs);

        NFSv4  and NFSv4.1 ;

        The iSCSI profile  for use in
        Internet Small Computer Systems Interface (iSCSI) Names;

        EAP ;

        The Nodeprep and Resourceprep profiles  for use in the Extensible Messaging and
        Presence Protocol (XMPP), and the XMPP to CPIM mapping  (the latter of these relies on the former);

        The Policy MIB profile  for use in
        the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP);

        The SASLprep profile  for use in
        the Simple Authentication and Security Layer (SASL), and SASL
        itself ;

        TLS ;

        IMAP4 using SASLprep ;

        The trace profile  for use with the
        SASL ANONYMOUS mechanism;

         The LDAP profile  for use with
        LDAP  and its authentication methods
        ;

        Plain SASL using SASLprep ;

        NNTP using SASLprep ;

        PKIX subject identification using LDAPprep ;

        Internet Application Protocol Collation Registry ;

        SMTP Auth using SASLprep ;

        POP3 Auth using SASLprep ;

        TLS SRP using SASLprep ;

        IRI and URI in XMPP ;

        PKIX CRL using LDAPprep ;

        IAX using Nameprep ;

        SASL SCRAM using SASLprep ;

        Remote management of Sieve using SASLprep ;

        The unicode-casemap Unicode Collation .
